lengths, fine\nterritory wools in original bags were\nbringing mostly 67 to 7(1 cents, scoured\nbasis, with an occasional odd lot becoming\navailable at prices slightly below this\nrange.\n\nMONEY MARKET.\nNEW YORK. Peb. 7 UP).\u2014Call money\nsteady; 1 per cent all day: prime com\nmercial paper 1 per cent: time loan*\nsteady: 60-90 days. 1V\u201e: 4-6 months. 1*4\nf*r cent: bankers' acceptances unchanged;\n60-90 days. *4-A: 4 months. A-*4: 5-6\nmonths. H-A. Rediscount rate. New York\nReserve Bank, 1 per cant.\ni\nU. S. STEEL LABOR\nConferences May Give Clue\nto Outcome of Vital\nPrice Struggle.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 7.\u2014Business\neyes are turned toward negotiations\nscheduled tor the coming week be\ntween C. I. O. representatives and tfte\nUnited States Steel Corp. in hope of\ncatching a hint to the outcome of a\nstruggle over prices.\nUncertain whether the 1937 fall in\nbasic commodities would lead to gen\neral downward revision of industrial\nprices, business circles have looked to\nbig steel's discussions with the C. I. O.\nfor renewal of a contract expiring\nFebruary 28 for possibly the new\nyear's first important clue to the wage\nprice question.\nSteel, it was pointed out, is the key\nmaterial of thousands of products or\nmodern machine industry, and United\nStates Steel, with about 35 per cent\nof the capacity, heads the machine\nage's No. 1 industry. Thus big steel's\nmoves are watched for leadership.\nPast Leadership Recalled.\nWidely recalled in Wall Street, as\nprice and wage maintenance has\ncome to the fore since the 1937 slump\nin raw materials, foodstuffs and in\ndustrial production, was the initiative\ntaken by United States Steel in Sep\ntember, 1931, for a wage cut during\nthe 1929-1933 deflationary movement.\nLeaders in .other industries followed\nthe steel wage revision.\nThe spotlight was shifted to the\nwage-price struggle by the recent con-j\ntention of President Roosevelt wages j\nshould be maintained and industrial!\nprices reduced in order to stimulate\nbusiness revival. Steel leaders have\ndiffered, holding prices could not be\ncut materially without change in pay\nrates, since wages are a major factor\nin the cost of steel.\nMeanwhile, scattered wage and pay\ncuts have been announced since the\nturn of the year, chiefly in textile\nmills, but pay scales generally appear\nto have held. Much potential buying\nin wholesale markets, including steel,\nhas been reported holding off until\nthe wage-price impasse Is settled.\nSituation Changes.\nThe industrial setting for the com\ning negotiations between the C. I. O.\nand Carnegie-Ulinois Steel, leading\noperating subsidiary of United States j\nSteel, has undergone one of the swift\nest changes in the country's records\nsince the Nation's biggest industrial\nunit nearly a year ago signed with\nthe Steel Workers\u2019 Organizing Com\nmittee, opening what some acclaimed\nthen as a new era in capital-labor re- 1\nlations in the United States. Prices\nwent up with wages, putting the cast\nof steel products back to pre-depres-!\nsion levels.\nShortly after the steel boast last\nMarch commodity \"prices turned down\nabruptly, followed by a decisive slumji\nin production in the autumn.\nIn the meanwhile, basic commodity\nquotations on the average have come\ndown about 30 per cent. Steel output\nin a record-breaking fall dropped\nfrom around 92 to nearly 19 per cent\nof capacity. Last week it was back\nto about 30 per cent, rated by finan- j\ncial analysts as a profitless level for1\nmajor producers.\nPressure for lower prices has been\nfelt nearly all down the line, but fin-'\nished steel quotations have held.\nINVESTING COMPANIES\nNEW YORK Feb 7 <4*.\u2014New York\nSecurity Dealers\u2019 Association:\n(Noon quotation*\nBid. Asked. 1\nAdmin Fd 2nd Inc 11 28 I7.no\nAm Business Shrs new 3.25 3.59\nAm Gen En Inc _t \u00abn .68\nAm Ins Stocks _ 4 50 4.75\nBancamer Blair 4.no 5.on j\nBankers Nat Inv Corp _ 2.175 2.87 5 i\nBasic Industry 3.02\